	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65541782"><p>gold can't be heated more than three times their boiling point, 1,948 degrees Fahrenheit (1,064 degrees Celsius)</p><p>

First of all, that is Gold's melting point (not boiling point). Second, what does "three times the temperature" even mean in this case - measured in Celsius, Fahrenheit or Kelvin, it gives different results...? And third - nature does not have such exact limits, so I understand that "three times" must be a rounded figure here.</p></div>
