	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65541914"><p><div class="quote"><p>gold can't be heated more than three times their boiling point, 1,948 degrees Fahrenheit (1,064 degrees Celsius)</p><p>

First of all, that is Gold's melting point (not boiling point). Second, what does "three times the temperature" even mean in this case - measured in Celsius, Fahrenheit or Kelvin, it gives different results...? And third - nature does not have such exact limits, so I understand that "three times" must be a rounded figure here.</p></div><p>It is a very well written paper, kudos to the researchers. And in an experiment that figuratively screams out for Kelvin Temperature, and that is what they actually used. </p><p>
Why the story used two virtually irrelevant temperature standards,  Fahrenheit and Celsius,  is beyond me. Perhaps the journalist discovered online conversion calculators? </p><p>

The only thing missing from the story was the standard "Scientists are stunned!" claim.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65541914">

